# {{app_name}}

A stryke web application generated by `s_web new`.

## Getting started

```sh
bin/server                 # start the dev server on http://localhost:3000
s_web g scaffold Post title:string body:text   # full CRUD for Post
s_web db migrate           # apply pending migrations
s_web routes               # list the route table
s_web console              # REPL with the app loaded
```

## Layout

```
{{app_name}}/
├── app/
│   ├── controllers/         # request handlers (extends ApplicationController)
│   ├── models/              # ORM classes (extends ApplicationRecord)
│   ├── views/               # ERB-shaped templates
│   └── helpers/             # functions auto-imported into views
├── bin/
│   └── server               # boot script
├── config/
│   ├── routes.stk           # routing DSL
│   ├── application.stk      # boot configuration
│   └── database.toml        # connection settings per environment
├── db/
│   ├── migrate/             # timestamped migration files
│   └── seeds.stk            # data loaded by `s_web db seed`
├── public/                  # static assets served at /
├── test/                    # tests (`s test` runs them)
└── stryke.toml              # framework + dependency manifest
```

## Conventions

Same as Rails — controllers are plural snake_case (`posts_controller.stk`),
models are singular PascalCase (`Post`), views live under
`app/views/<controller>/<action>.html.erb`. Migrations are timestamped:
`db/migrate/20260430153012_create_posts.stk`.

## Stryke web vs Rails

The DSL is intentionally Rails-shaped: `route "GET /posts/:id" ~> "posts#show"`,
`class PostsController extends ApplicationController`, `class Post extends ApplicationRecord`.
The runtime ships as stryke builtins so there's no per-request import or
boot-time gem load — the framework is part of the language.
